The paper deals with a distributed coordination task involving multiple parties exchanging assets across multiple blockchains, which falls under the category of cryptography and security (cs.CR). The protocol used in the paper involves hashed timelock contracts, which is a technique used in distributed computing (cs.DC) and distributed systems (cs.DS). The paper also discusses the properties of the associated directed graph, which is a topic in graph theory and algorithms (cs.DS, cs.SC). Finally, the time and communication complexity of the protocol are analyzed, which falls under the category of machine learning (cs.LG).
